words.definition: The quality of being able to perform; a natural or acquired skill.
words.etymology: From Old French abletΓ©, from Latin habilitas.
words.example: She has the ability to solve complex mathematical problems.

words.definition: Concerning or in relation to something.
words.example: He talked about his experiences in the meeting.

words.definition: In or to a foreign country or countries.
words.etymology: From Middle English abroad, on broad (on a wide expanse).
words.example: She studied abroad for one year in France.

words.definition: Not qualified or diminished in any way; total.
words.example: She has absolute confidence in her decision.
